<dl id="n11083c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11083c">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11083c"> 83(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 21&frasl;6 sunrise turns red / altarslab Stoneheng</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Pilgrimage to Stonehenge.</b> <font color="green">[...]</font> In the moonlit hours before to-day&apos;s dawn Salisbury Plain was the vast stage of a Midsummer Night fantasy. / Long before midnight the shire road which runs beside the great Druidical remains of <mark>Stonehenge</mark> was crowded with people who had come to see <mark>its first rays fall blood-red on the ancient altar</mark> in the Sun-worshippers&apos; ruined temple. Only at its rising on the longest say of the year does the sun cover completely this altar on which, it is believed, the Druids offered human sacrifices. <small> <a name="DM23jun24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#DM23jun24"><cite title="source">Daily Mail</cite></a> (23 June 1924) 7/4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
